This may not be the best way to handle this but I added this above your `createNewItem` in your `App/index.js`

```
  shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps, nextState){
    if (this.state.restoOriginales !== nextState.restoOriginales){
      console.log(&quot;NUEVO ITEM&quot;, nextState.restoOriginales);
      //put your setState code here with nextState.restoOriginales
    }
    return true;
  }
```
React documentation says
```
shouldComponentUpdate() is invoked before 
rendering when new props or state are being received. Defaults to true. 
```

All this basically does is force the parent to be updated. To be honest there is probably a better way of handling this, but here is one solution that should work for you.

The issue here is that `setState` is async, so `console.log` won&#39;t show the new state straight away. To achieve that you need to use a callback for `setState`:
```
 createNewItem = event =&gt; {
    const newList = [event, ...this.state.restoOriginales];
    this.setState({ restoOriginales: newList }, () =&gt; { // Use callback here
      console.log(&quot;NUEVO ITEM&quot;, this.state.restoOriginales);
    });
  };
```

Also you&#39;ll need to redirect back to homepage or otherwise remove the form after an item is saved.

